Lab 3: Assignment (Making ML model of Linear Regression) :¶

This lab's task is to use the California Housing Prices Dataset from Kaggle to conduct a univariate linear regression. This is a crucial idea in outcome prediction: a univariate linear regression model. Three distinct models must be performed, each matching a different independent variable ({given below}) with the median house value (dependent variable). It's similar to investigating the effects of three distinct data points on property values. This practical exercise will assist us in applying the power of linear regression to find patterns and relationships within the data. Let's begin this enlightening adventure now!

- Balbhadra Prajapati (8873745)

Goals:¶

We have to make 3 different models using in total 4 variables, that includes:

  • median_house_value
  • median_income
  • population
  • households

We need to create a model that can forecast the values of houses given any single value of median_income, population, or households with the aid of these four factors. By taking this action, we are able to create a machine learning model that, given specific features, can estimate the values of houses in California. For those who are willing to purchase a house in a Californian location, this application can be quite beneficial.

*predicted prices are not exact as the currenty market rates.*

Conclusion of Exploratory Data Analysis:¶

importent EDA insites:

  • There exist 207 residences that lack any bedrooms.
  • There are 20640 cases in all, and the majority of them include values rather than bedrooms.
  • Within the block, the most expensive and chipest house costs $500001 and $15,000, respectively.
  • Houses are roughly 29 years old on average.
  • Each block in California has roughly 538 bedrooms.
  • Approximately 500 households reside in a single block.

1. Univariate Linear Regression using Median_Income to predict Value of House¶

In [ ]:
sns.set(style="whitegrid")
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
scatter_plot = sns.scatterplot(x="median_income", y="median_house_value", data=df, alpha=0.7, marker='d', hue="population", palette="viridis", edgecolor=None, s=80)
plt.title("Relationship between Median Income and Median House Value", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Median Income", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Median House Value", fontsize=14)
plt.xticks(fontsize=12)
plt.yticks(fontsize=12)
plt.show()

The above graph shows the relationship between Median Income and Median House Value. By just observing this graph, we can say that an individual having 60K USD of income can probably have Median House Value of around 300K USD.

In [ ]:
x1 = df[["median_income"]]
y1 = df[["median_house_value"]]
model = LinearRegression()

The Mean Absolute error is 62625.9337911434
The Mean squared error is 7011311502.929527
Variance score is 0.4734474918071989
R2 Score is 0.47344749180719903
  1. In the provided dataset, the average of the absolute errors of all the data-points is approximately 62625.93 US dollers.
  2. In the provided dataset, the average square of the errors of all the data-points is 7011311502.93 US dollers.
  3. This result indicates that approximately 47.3% of the volatility in this dataset can be explained by our model.
  4. The R2 result indicates that the model will accurately predict about 47.3% of unknown samples.

After the model training, we are able to predict the value of a house based on the basis of median income of an individual par block for the data points for which the model is not trained on, typically it is called predicted value for the unseen data.Once the model has been trained, we may forecast a home's worth based on the median income of a specific par block for the data points that the model has not been trained on. This is known as the forecasted value for the unseen data.

Let's examine why the data point limit is approximately $500,000.

This is the intriguing case right now. As you can see, most people living in a block are in the 07000 range. Nevertheless, this model's forecast does not state the same thing. In theory, a line should be drawn between those sites, but there is a block with a population of 36,000. As a result, the model became confused and began to anticipate outcomes incorrectly.

Summary of the Report.¶

The first model is the most ideal and has the best goodness of fit out of the three. There are some biseness or outliers in the other videos. The accompanying table helps us to comprehend it.

Model Mean Absolute Error Mean Squared Error Variance Score R2 Score
Model1 (median income) 62625.93 7011311502.93 0.4734 0.4734
Model2 (population) 91153.82 13307412412.39 0.0006 0.0006
Model3 (number of households) 90802.74 13257776904.73 0.0043 0.0043

With respect to the three models, Model 1 performs the best, as seen by its lower MAE and MSE values, as well as its significantly higher Variance Score and R2 Score. In comparison to Model1, Models 2 and 3 show more mistakes and less predictive power. It could be required to do additional analysis and refining in order to improve the models' forecasting skills.
